From: Raffaella del Prete <raffaellanz@icloud.com>
Sent: Thursday, 26 June 2025 11:21 am
To: Chris Cornwall <Chris.Cornwall@tower.co.nz>
Subject: Re: Tower Claim - C90306048

Hi Chris, Thank you again for sending through the Asset Restore scope of wo=
rks and for all your efforts in helping move my claim forward. I=E2=80=99ve=
 reviewed the document and truly appreciate the work being done to progress=
 the reinstatement for 23


Hi Chris,

Thank you again for sending through the Asset Restore scope of works and fo=
r all your efforts in helping move my claim forward. I=E2=80=99ve reviewed =
the document and truly appreciate the work being done to progress the reins=
tatement for 23 Mays Street, Devonport.

As we discussed over the phone, before we proceed, I=E2=80=99d like to rais=
e a few questions=E2=80=94I hope you don=E2=80=99t mind me checking in this=
 way. My goal is to ensure everything is addressed safely and in the right =
order:

  *   A qualified master electrician has assessed the house and advised it=
=E2=80=99s not electrically safe, especially with the new switchboard and w=
iring. Has a formal licensed electrical inspection been scheduled to confir=
m safety before re-entry?
  *   As we spoke, there are structural beam damages, and the significant s=
moke traveling through floors, walls, and out all sides of the roof suggest=
s extensive heat stress. The wetness and dampness from firefighters might h=
ave worsened these structural issues. Would it be prudent to have a structu=
ral engineer assess the building before any removal or cleaning begins?
  *   Regarding asbestos, the quote mentions less than 10m=C2=B2 of ACM mat=
erial for removal, but the attached photo shows the damaged lower deck sect=
ion is closely connected to the main deck, possibly indicating more extensi=
ve involvement. Would a full asbestos inspection be a wise step to rule out=
 broader risks?
  *   The gas unit, exposed to heat and smoke, concerns me. Has a technicia=
n been arranged to inspect the system and fittings for safety?
  *   Lastly, the firefighting water use and a leak shutdown suggest potent=
ial moisture or mould damage in hidden areas. Should we arrange an assessme=
nt for water or mould damage before reinstatement?

On a related note, I was wondering about the work sequence. The quote focus=
es on cleaning for reinstatement, but might it be better to start with remo=
val and cleaning just for assessment? This could allow engineers and specia=
lists to evaluate hidden damage (e.g., behind linings) and ensure a safe re=
storation plan=E2=80=94does that sound reasonable?

I=E2=80=99d also kindly ask if you could share plans to help me stay inform=
ed and involved, and if we should regularly catch up=E2=80=94perhaps weekly=
 via email or a quick chat? That would be really helpful for me.

I am happy to see we are moving forward and very keen as the accommodation =
allowance is limited, and would love to return home and resume normal life =
as soon as it=E2=80=99s safe. These questions come from a place of care and=
 collaboration, and I really appreciate your time in considering them.

Thanks again for your support. I look forward to your thoughts.

Kind regards,
Raffaella del Prete

[cid:image004.jpg@01DBE6A7.72EAF7D0]

[cid:image005.jpg@01DBE6A7.72EAF7D0]
[cid:image006.jpg@01DBE6A7.72EAF7D0]

